Science education, in its current iteration, emphasizes understanding and retaining the canon of science. Concepts that are "true". The hard facts. In the pursuit of this, we tend to approach science education as an attempt to get more children into the [[STEM pipeline\|STEM pipeline]]. This approach excludes non-STEM career students, and that exclusion leads to a general attitude of adults who throw their hands in the air and claim that "science" is not for them. Or they're not good at math. Or whatever similar sentiment. 

Rather than focusing on learning for the sake of learning and to get people into a career pipeline. Could we not perhaps explore opportunities to create meaningful, transformative experiences for students through learning? Not just arduous, stressful or standards-focused learning?

[[04. Sources/@pughScienceArtExperience2007\|Pugh and Girod (2007)]] propose a framework for science education that takes its page from [[Dewey\|Dewey]] and his philosophy on [[01. Personal/Values and Strengths/ðŸ’› Aesthetics\|ðŸ’› Aesthetics]] and [[transformative experiences\|transformative experiences]]. The framework aims to create transcendent experiences for learners when they learn new information, providing them the opportunity to connect the new knowledge they've been given with their out-of-class lives. 

Dewey is well-known for his work on learning through doing, which Kolb drew on as he developed the [[Experiential Learning Model\|Experiential Learning Model]] (along with Kurt Lewin and Jean Piaget's work). Dewey was also fascinated with the idea of aesthetics. 

Dewey not just explored the "Learning through Experience", but "Experience through learning".

In short, how can we provide learners with meaningful experiences derived from learning new things? 

Dewey explored these ideas in his writings about art and aesthetics, and he had some specific conceptualizations of aesthetics, which is a whole area of study that goes beyond "things looking pretty" or even beyond Art as a sole domain of aesthetics. 

Dewey was interested in the idea of "Experiences" (the capitalization is my addition, but I seek to emphasize how it differs from everyday experiences). 

A Deweyian "Experience" (or a transformative experience) is a complete, memorable event that stands out from other events and experiences. Anticipation is key to an Experience, which follows an arc of rising and falling intensity, marking the beginning and end of the Experience. The outcome of an Experience, and what sets it apart from day-to-day life, is that it sparks a transformation. That transformation can be a change in one's relationship to oneself or the world around them because of a new and valued perspective.

When it comes to STEM education, where art can lead to transformative experiences, ideas can be the catalysts for transformation. Ideas are different from concepts. They are different from facts. Ideas are lively. They have potential. They illicit action and response and new ways of thinking of and acting in the world.

Ideas relate to transformative experiences in that they involve a similar build-and-resolution arc of anticipation: starting with how we can be different in the world and resolving when we act and the resulting consequences.

Pugh (2002)'s construction of a [[02. Notes/Notes/Transformative experience\|Transformative Experience]] is one that: 
1. Actively uses the concept
2. Expands perception
3. Expands the value

>[!quote] With today's emphasis on standards , proficiency testing, and international comparisons, it is easy to forget the artful side of science; it is easy to forget- or fail to even realize- that science has a potential to enrich everyday life, vitalize experience, and provide us with aesthetic satisfaction
>- Pugh and Girod 2007

>[!quote] We are more likely to ask questions like, "Do students understand the concepts correctly?" than "Do the concepts make any difference in the students' everyday, out-of-school lives?"
>- Pugh and Girod 2007
